# Alembic Commands Cheat-Sheet

```
# Initialize Alembic in your project
alembic init alembic
```

Set up Alembic folder structure (`alembic/`, `versions/`, `env.py`, etc.).

```
alembic revision -m "description"
```

Create a new **blank** migration; you’ll write schema changes manually.

```
alembic revision --autogenerate -m "description"
```

Auto-generate a migration comparing your current models to the database schema.

```
alembic upgrade head
```

Apply all migrations to bring database to the latest version.

```
alembic upgrade <revision_id>
```

Upgrade schema to a specific revision.

```
alembic downgrade -1
```

Revert the most recent migration.

```
alembic downgrade <revision_id>
```

Downgrade database schema to a specific past revision.

```
alembic current
```

Show which revision is currently applied in the database.

```
alembic history
```

List all migrations (past & future) in sequential order.

```
alembic show <revision_id>
```

Display the details (upgrade/downgrade code) of a given migration file.

```
alembic stamp head
```

Mark the database as if all migrations up to “head” are applied, without running them. Useful when schema structure already matches models but migrations weren’t applied.

```
alembic heads
```

Show all current heads (latest migrations); helps to detect branching (multiple heads).

```
alembic merge <rev_id1> <rev_id2> -m "merge message"
```

Merge two divergent heads into one. Resolve branches when multiple migrations were created in parallel.

---

## Quick Reference Flow

1. Modify your SQLAlchemy models (add / remove / change something).
2. Run:

   ```
   alembic revision --autogenerate -m "your message"
   ```

3. Review the generated migration file (upgrade() / downgrade()). Make any needed manual fixes.
4. Apply migration:

   ```
   alembic upgrade head
   ```

5. If needed rollback:

   ```
   alembic downgrade -1
   ```

   or to a specific revision.